WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.930 --> 00:00:03.585
Prof: Okay.
 

00:00:03.585 --> 00:00:09.010
Now we're going to talk about a
different kind of ecology.

00:00:09.010 --> 00:00:11.882
We're going to talk about the
flow of energy and matter

00:00:11.882 --> 00:00:13.000
through ecosystems.
 

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.329
Up until now we have been
dealing mostly with the

00:00:17.329 --> 00:00:22.380
biological interactions of
organisms with each other,

00:00:22.380 --> 00:00:24.660
with organisms of other
species, and with some

00:00:24.660 --> 00:00:27.246
physiological ecology where
they're dealing with the

00:00:27.246 --> 00:00:30.490
physical and chemical problems
presented by the environment.

00:00:30.490 --> 00:00:35.632
But now we're going to look at
the energy and flow of materials

00:00:35.632 --> 00:00:41.075
through ecosystems and biomes,
and in the world as a whole,

00:00:41.075 --> 00:00:46.003
as a paradigm that's driven
primarily by physics and

00:00:46.003 --> 00:00:47.260
chemistry.
 

00:00:47.260 --> 00:00:51.375
Now there are differences
between ecosystem and community

00:00:51.375 --> 00:00:54.315
ecology, and I think that
this--you know,

00:00:54.315 --> 00:00:57.770
some of this is a little bit
light-hearted;

00:00:57.770 --> 00:01:01.590
some of it is dead serious.
 

00:01:01.590 --> 00:01:05.227
So in ecosystem ecology,
one is primary concerned about

00:01:05.227 --> 00:01:08.992
the flow of matter and energy,
and in community ecology

00:01:08.992 --> 00:01:11.819
primarily with inter-specific
interactions.

00:01:11.819 --> 00:01:13.680
The paradigm here is
thermodynamics.

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:18.418
So the mass balance equations,
the second law,

00:01:18.418 --> 00:01:22.420
entropy increases,
things like that.

00:01:22.420 --> 00:01:26.739
Here the issues are primarily
competition, predation and

00:01:26.739 --> 00:01:28.390
history, and space.
 

00:01:28.390 --> 00:01:29.930
Okay?
 

00:01:29.930 --> 00:01:32.677
The kinds of measurements that
get made are physical,

00:01:32.677 --> 00:01:35.849
chemical and geological here,
and they're biological here.

00:01:35.849 --> 00:01:39.274
So you don't see Latin names
and you don't see species names

00:01:39.274 --> 00:01:42.861
in ecosystem ecology;
and they are definitely present

00:01:42.861 --> 00:01:46.060
and they're important in
community ecology.

00:01:46.060 --> 00:01:50.507
The way that scientists chunk
reality in order to make it

00:01:50.507 --> 00:01:53.050
manageable is quite different.
 

00:01:53.050 --> 00:01:55.545
In ecosystem ecology,
they worry about ecosystem

00:01:55.545 --> 00:01:58.200
compartments and stuff that
moves between them,

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:01.903
and in community ecology they
worry mostly about species

00:02:01.903 --> 00:02:05.269
abundances and how it changes in
time and space.

00:02:05.269 --> 00:02:09.199
So the connection here is
primarily to the biosphere.

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:15.075
Here people are looking upward
at larger, more complicated,

00:02:15.075 --> 00:02:19.436
bigger kinds of things;
and in the community ecology

00:02:19.436 --> 00:02:22.762
they're mostly looking downward
at how the community

00:02:22.762 --> 00:02:26.283
interactions are driving the
population dynamics of the

00:02:26.283 --> 00:02:27.848
individual species.
 

00:02:27.848 --> 00:02:32.639
So the connection here is to
biology and the connection here

00:02:32.639 --> 00:02:33.940
is to geology.
 

00:02:33.940 --> 00:02:37.693
And the two things definitely
connect to each other,

00:02:37.693 --> 00:02:38.210
okay?
 

00:02:38.210 --> 00:02:41.348
So they have strong
implications for each other.

00:02:41.348 --> 00:02:45.537
But, as you know,
academic specialties themselves

00:02:45.537 --> 00:02:47.649
evolve,
and people develop different

00:02:47.649 --> 00:02:50.348
paradigms and different language
for dealing with problems,

00:02:50.348 --> 00:02:54.960
and they have tended to remain
isolated from one another,

00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:58.286
and, unfortunately,
sometimes they have even tended

00:02:58.286 --> 00:03:02.444
to denigrate one another,
although they're both perfectly

00:03:02.444 --> 00:03:05.628
valid ways of trying to analyze
the world;

00:03:05.628 --> 00:03:10.120
they're really just trying to
answer different questions.

00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:13.451
So today what I'm going to do
is I'm just going to outline

00:03:13.451 --> 00:03:16.784
energy flow, cycles of materials
and biogeochemical cycles

00:03:16.784 --> 00:03:18.128
through ecosystems.
 

00:03:18.128 --> 00:03:22.098
I'm dealing with it at a fairly
descriptive level.

00:03:22.098 --> 00:03:31.150
There are methods of making
this paradigm very quantitative.

00:03:31.150 --> 00:03:35.931
And if you get interested in
it, really the place to go is

00:03:35.931 --> 00:03:36.770
geology.
 

00:03:36.770 --> 00:03:39.229
Ruth Blake does this kind of
thing.

00:03:39.229 --> 00:03:41.270
She's a biogeochemist in
geology.

00:03:41.270 --> 00:03:46.204
This is a part of the world
that has important implications

00:03:46.204 --> 00:03:50.287
for global warming,
and which is driven mostly by

00:03:50.287 --> 00:03:52.840
things that have one cell.
 

00:03:52.840 --> 00:03:53.680
Okay?
 

00:03:53.680 --> 00:04:01.082
Whether they're algae or
bacteria, they are the main

00:04:01.082 --> 00:04:06.599
transducer between life and
geology.

00:04:06.599 --> 00:04:08.568
Now what is an ecosystem?
 

00:04:08.568 --> 00:04:11.824
Well it's one of those sort of
abstract terms that gets

00:04:11.824 --> 00:04:14.358
operationalized in a lot of
different ways,

00:04:14.358 --> 00:04:16.709
depending on who's doing the
study.

00:04:16.709 --> 00:04:20.834
But generally speaking it's the
organisms in a particular place,

00:04:20.834 --> 00:04:24.762
plus the physical and chemical
environment with which they're

00:04:24.762 --> 00:04:25.810
interacting.
 

00:04:25.810 --> 00:04:30.129
And it's often a local example
of some kind of biome.

00:04:30.129 --> 00:04:30.610
Okay?
 

00:04:30.610 --> 00:04:33.244
So it could be a local chunk of
tundra, a local chunk of

00:04:33.244 --> 00:04:34.250
rainforest, a pond.
 

00:04:34.250 --> 00:04:38.269
It could be an upwelling area
off Peru.

00:04:38.269 --> 00:04:41.839
It could be an alpine forest.
 

00:04:41.839 --> 00:04:45.220
It could be a lot of different
things.

00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:48.180
And people study how energy
flows,

00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:52.682
and so the paradigm basically,
at least for things that are in

00:04:52.682 --> 00:04:56.521
the part of the planet that are
driven by the primary

00:04:56.521 --> 00:05:00.704
productivity of plants,
it starts with photosynthesis,

00:05:00.704 --> 00:05:04.156
and the annual production is
usually determined by

00:05:04.156 --> 00:05:09.048
temperature and moisture;
certainly for terrestrial

00:05:09.048 --> 00:05:10.449
ecosystems.
 

00:05:10.449 --> 00:05:14.514
Left out of this description is
all of the chemosynthetic

00:05:14.514 --> 00:05:19.110
activity which occurs in deep,
black, dark water at mid-ocean

00:05:19.110 --> 00:05:22.139
ridges,
and which is occurring in the

00:05:22.139 --> 00:05:26.636
subterranean part of the
biosphere that goes down- up to

00:05:26.636 --> 00:05:31.029
say five or ten kilometers,
where there are bacteria that

00:05:31.029 --> 00:05:33.019
are living deep in the ground.
 

00:05:33.019 --> 00:05:36.642
And actually the pervasive
influx of life,

00:05:36.642 --> 00:05:40.973
into the subterranean
environment, is an important

00:05:40.973 --> 00:05:45.040
part in the biogeochemistry of
the planet;

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:47.379
that's not covered here.
 

00:05:47.379 --> 00:05:52.786
If we look around by,
just by surface area,

00:05:52.786 --> 00:05:57.420
the planet's about 65% open
ocean;

00:05:57.420 --> 00:06:01.706
it's about 5% continental shelf;
desert's about 5%--that's

00:06:01.706 --> 00:06:05.144
extreme desert,
okay, that's just about nothing

00:06:05.144 --> 00:06:08.706
on the surface;
semidesert, so Sahel,

00:06:08.706 --> 00:06:13.036
that kind of area,
about almost 3Â½,

00:06:13.036 --> 00:06:15.759
4%;
3% tropical rainforest;

00:06:15.759 --> 00:06:17.250
and so forth.
 

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:21.779
The idea here is you can take
the planet and you can define

00:06:21.779 --> 00:06:25.920
different categories of the way
things live on it,

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:28.100
just by surface area,
and break it down,

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:29.670
and it looks like this.
 

00:06:29.670 --> 00:06:33.170
So here, if you were just to
look at that,

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:35.901
you would say, "Well,
open ocean, continental shelf,

00:06:35.901 --> 00:06:39.730
desert and rainforest are the
main biomes on the planet."

00:06:39.730 --> 00:06:41.360
That's just by surface area.
 

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:45.339
If you look at net primary
production per square meter,

00:06:45.339 --> 00:06:47.920
you get a totally different
view.

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:48.790
Okay?
 

00:06:48.790 --> 00:06:52.543
So this is just by surface
area, and this is by primary

00:06:52.543 --> 00:06:54.629
production per square meter.
 

00:06:54.629 --> 00:07:00.279
Look at how lousy the open
oceans are.

00:07:00.279 --> 00:07:02.939
Open oceans are deserts.
 

00:07:02.939 --> 00:07:06.100
Why are open oceans deserts?
 

00:07:06.100 --> 00:07:06.879
Student:  No fresh water.
 

00:07:06.879 --> 00:07:07.639
Prof: What?
 

00:07:07.639 --> 00:07:08.399
Student:  No fresh water.
 

00:07:08.399 --> 00:07:10.613
Prof: No,
it's not that there's no fresh

00:07:10.613 --> 00:07:11.000
water.
 

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.055
What do you need if you're
going to make an ecosystem

00:07:14.055 --> 00:07:14.819
productive?
 

00:07:14.819 --> 00:07:16.980
Student:  Zooplankton
&gt;.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:17.879
Prof: They need
nutrients.

00:07:17.879 --> 00:07:19.120
Where are they going to get it?
 

00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:21.920
Student:  Weathering
or--

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:23.653
Prof: They could get it
from weathering or they could

00:07:23.653 --> 00:07:24.360
get it from upwelling.
 

00:07:24.360 --> 00:07:25.540
Where does upwelling occur?
 

00:07:25.540 --> 00:07:27.028
Student: On a costal
reef.

00:07:27.028 --> 00:07:28.699
Prof: Yeah,
continental margins.

00:07:28.699 --> 00:07:31.985
Get out in the middle of the
ocean and there's actually a

00:07:31.985 --> 00:07:35.860
tremendous amount of fertilizer
there but it's five miles down,

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:39.199
three to five miles down,
and you just can't get it up.

00:07:39.199 --> 00:07:41.822
It's sealed off,
because the top of the ocean is

00:07:41.822 --> 00:07:44.279
warm and the bottom of the ocean
is cold,

00:07:44.279 --> 00:07:46.487
and there's no way that cold
water can come up through warm

00:07:46.487 --> 00:07:48.769
water,
unless you have Coriolis force

00:07:48.769 --> 00:07:51.550
or wind or something like that
driving it.

00:07:51.550 --> 00:07:54.170
So that's why the open oceans
are deserts.

00:07:54.170 --> 00:07:57.047
You'll notice that tropical
rainforests are highly

00:07:57.047 --> 00:07:58.810
productive per square meter.
 

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:01.319
In general forests are pretty
productive.

00:08:01.319 --> 00:08:03.610
Swamps and streams are very
productive.

00:08:03.610 --> 00:08:07.591
Algal beds and reefs are quite
productive, and so are

00:08:07.591 --> 00:08:08.509
estuaries.
 

00:08:08.509 --> 00:08:11.930
So if you want to go someplace
where you're--

00:08:11.930 --> 00:08:14.860
you know, you're a naturalist,
you like creepy-crawlies,

00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:17.358
you want frogs in your pocket,
you want to see something new

00:08:17.358 --> 00:08:20.589
for Christmas,
you go to these places;

00:08:20.589 --> 00:08:25.879
that's where you'll see a lot
of stuff.

00:08:25.879 --> 00:08:28.569
Okay?
 

00:08:28.569 --> 00:08:33.023
So right there you already know
where the prospecting is good,

00:08:33.023 --> 00:08:36.090
if you like to see lots of
biodiversity.

00:08:36.090 --> 00:08:40.432
Now if you look at percent
contribution to global primary

00:08:40.432 --> 00:08:43.782
production,
the open oceans again crop up,

00:08:43.782 --> 00:08:47.928
and that is because there's
just so darn much of them.

00:08:47.928 --> 00:08:50.695
If you're out there in space,
looking at the world,

00:08:50.695 --> 00:08:53.904
you realize that you can fit
all of the continents into the

00:08:53.904 --> 00:08:56.291
Pacific Ocean;
it's bigger than all the

00:08:56.291 --> 00:08:57.740
continents put together.
 

00:08:57.740 --> 00:09:00.735
And most of it is open ocean;
most of it is low primary

00:09:00.735 --> 00:09:02.149
productivity open ocean.
 

00:09:02.149 --> 00:09:04.868
But there's just so darn much
of it that on the planetary

00:09:04.868 --> 00:09:07.149
scale it's making a pretty good
contribution.

00:09:07.149 --> 00:09:10.298
And the tropical rainforests
are big enough so that even

00:09:10.298 --> 00:09:13.450
though they're only 3 and a half
or 4% of the globe,

00:09:13.450 --> 00:09:16.488
they have such high primary
productivity that they're

00:09:16.488 --> 00:09:17.950
kicking in quite a bit.
 

00:09:17.950 --> 00:09:20.591
And the others,
even though they are

00:09:20.591 --> 00:09:24.817
productive, occupy such a small
portion of the globe that

00:09:24.817 --> 00:09:27.759
they're not contributing that
much.

00:09:27.759 --> 00:09:32.520
Okay, so this is an overall
view of energy flow on the

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:37.371
planet, at least for the
photosynthetically driven part

00:09:37.371 --> 00:09:38.990
of the planet.
 

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:43.529
The sun is sending in the
energy.

00:09:43.529 --> 00:09:47.578
And by the way,
any idea of roughly how much of

00:09:47.578 --> 00:09:53.037
the sunlight that comes into the
planet is actually captured by

00:09:53.037 --> 00:09:53.830
life?
 

00:09:53.830 --> 00:09:57.110
How efficient has the planet
become at capturing photons?

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:06.947
Does it capture 50%,
10%, 1%, 1/10^(th) of a

00:10:06.947 --> 00:10:08.399
percent?
 

00:10:08.399 --> 00:10:09.269
A guess?
 

00:10:09.269 --> 00:10:11.990
How many for 50% Hands up.
 

00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:14.029
How many for 10%?
 

00:10:14.029 --> 00:10:14.899
Hands up.
 

00:10:14.899 --> 00:10:15.879
A couple.
 

00:10:15.879 --> 00:10:16.860
How many for 1%?
 

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:18.908
Hands up.
 

00:10:18.908 --> 00:10:20.769
How many for 1/10^(th) of a
percent?

00:10:20.769 --> 00:10:21.700
Hands up.
 

00:10:21.700 --> 00:10:25.070
See the grad students think
it's a 1/10^(th) of a percent.

00:10:25.070 --> 00:10:26.269
It's a small amount.
 

00:10:26.269 --> 00:10:29.399
I don't know the precise
number, but it's down between

00:10:29.399 --> 00:10:30.700
1/10 and 1% I think.
 

00:10:30.700 --> 00:10:34.514
So even after 3.5 billion years
of evolutionary history,

00:10:34.514 --> 00:10:38.398
the planet has not become
terribly efficient at capturing

00:10:38.398 --> 00:10:39.298
sunlight.
 

00:10:39.298 --> 00:10:43.813
Freeman Dyson has got this
definition of different kinds of

00:10:43.813 --> 00:10:45.058
civilizations.
 

00:10:45.058 --> 00:10:47.758
One of the stages of
civilization would be when you

00:10:47.758 --> 00:10:50.833
can put a sphere around an
entire solar system and capture

00:10:50.833 --> 00:10:53.964
all of the photons coming off of
the sun and harness it for

00:10:53.964 --> 00:10:55.529
running a civilization.
 

00:10:55.529 --> 00:10:58.908
That would capture the entire
solar output.

00:10:58.908 --> 00:11:03.200
Well, you know,
we are a tiny little dot on the

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:07.397
face of the sun,
and we're taking 1/10^(th) to

00:11:07.397 --> 00:11:09.450
1% of its photons.
 

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:12.697
So this isn't a very big number
when you look at the solar

00:11:12.697 --> 00:11:13.210
output.
 

00:11:13.210 --> 00:11:18.154
What happens is that basically
algae, primarily algae,

00:11:18.154 --> 00:11:22.072
but also trees and all other
larger plants,

00:11:22.072 --> 00:11:24.220
are capturing this.
 

00:11:24.220 --> 00:11:27.120
Then the herbivores are eating
the plants.

00:11:27.120 --> 00:11:29.288
The primary carnivores are
eating the herbivores.

00:11:29.288 --> 00:11:33.408
The secondary carnivores are
eating the primary carnivores.

